🧠 How Node decides “what runs next”

Imagine Node has 4 priority buckets.
After your normal code finishes, Node checks these buckets in order.

1️⃣ process.nextTick() — “DO THIS RIGHT NOW”
Highest priority. Dangerous if abused.
What it is:
A special Node-only queue

Runs before anything else

Even before Promises

Simple analogy:

You’re in a meeting, and your boss whispers:

“Stop everything. Handle this NOW.”

That’s process.nextTick.

Key points:

Runs immediately after current code

Can block everything if overused

Timers, Promises, I/O → all get ignored until this finishes

Why it’s risky:

If you keep adding nextTick inside nextTick, Node never moves on.

🔥 Server freeze potential.







2️⃣ Promise.then() — “Run this right after”
High priority, but safer.
What it is:
Microtask queue
Used by Promises and async/await
Simple analogy:
You tell yourself:
“As soon as I finish this task, I’ll do this small thing.”
That’s a microtask.

Key points:

Runs after nextTick

Runs before timers

Used everywhere in modern JS

Important:

Promises can delay timers,
but they can’t completely kill the event loop like nextTick.









3️⃣ setTimeout() — “Do this later (at least X ms)”
Not instant. Ever.
What it is:
Goes into Timers phase
0ms means “minimum delay”, not instant

Simple analogy:

You set an alarm:
“Do this after some time has passed.”

Even 0ms means:

“After Node checks other stuff.”

Key points:

Timing is not guaranteed

Depends on system load

Can be delayed if Node is busy

That’s why setTimeout(0) ≠ immediate.
